An abstract class is a class from which you cannot create an object directly.
It serves as a base class that defines a common structure or interface for its derived classes.
An abstract class must have at least one pure virtual function.

Key Properties
âœ… It can include both normal functions and variables, along with pure virtual functions.
ğŸš« You canâ€™t make an object of an abstract class.
ğŸ§  Itâ€™s mainly used for upcasting â€” treating a derived class object as a base class reference or pointer.
âš™ï¸ If a derived class doesnâ€™t define all pure virtual functions, it also becomes abstract.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Base {
public:
    // Pure Virtual Function â†’ makes Base an abstract class
    virtual void show() = 0;  
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void show() {
        cout << "Virtual Function implemented in Derived class";
    }
};

int main() {
    // Base b; âŒ Not allowed â€” cannot create an object of abstract class
    Base *ptr;        // Pointer to Base class
    Derived d;  // Object of Derived class
    ptr = &d;     // Upcasting (Derived â†’ Base pointer)
    ptr->show();      // Calls Derived's implementation
}

Output Virtual Function implemented in Derived class


If Derived Doesnâ€™t Override

If Derived does not provide its own version of show(), then it also becomes an abstract class â€” and you still canâ€™t create an object of it.

ğŸ”¹ Why Abstract Classes Are Useful
They help achieve runtime polymorphism.
They define a blueprint or interface for all derived classes.
They ensure consistency among related classes in a program.
